# Toolbar — back, title, and tabs on the left

When a horizontal **sub-bar / toolbar / chrome strip** combines:

- A **back** (or “up”) control  
- A **contextual title** (screen or entity name)  
- **Mode tabs** (e.g. `Picker` with `.segmented`, or equivalent tab buttons)

then lay them out as **one leading cluster**, left to right:

**Back → Title → Tabs** (contiguous, small consistent spacing between items).

- **Do not** put a flexible `Spacer()` (or `frame(maxWidth: .infinity)` on the title) **between** the title and the tabs — that pushes tabs away from the title toward the center or trailing edge.
- **Leading cluster width:** wrap **Back + Title + Tabs** in an inner `HStack` and apply **`fixedSize(horizontal: true, vertical: false)`** on that stack so a **segmented `Picker` does not stretch** to fill the bar (which visually detaches tabs from the title). Keep the title to a **modest `maxWidth`** (e.g. ≤ **100** for a callsign-style mission name) so long names truncate instead of pushing the tab control.
- After the leading cluster, use **`Spacer(minLength: …)`** (or equivalent) so **secondary actions** (delete, overflow menu, save, etc.) sit on the **trailing** edge.
- **Destructive** or **screen-level** actions belong **trailing**, not inside the back/title/tabs group.

Apply this pattern for new inspectors and when refactoring existing strips (e.g. mission workspace, settings subtrees, any “drill-in” header).
